<TITLE> Credit Suisse, Allianz weigh on European shares </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 FRANKFURT, March 20 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European shares fell early on Thursday, tracking US stocks, as a profit warning from Credit Suisse and a bearish forecast from Allianz kept credit market woes firmly in the spotlight. By 0810 GMT, the pan-European FTSEurofirst 300 index was down 0.8 percent at 1,220.05 points. The index fell 0.9 percent on Wednesday, mainly due to technology and telecom stocks. "Markets are very nervous. We remain negative. As soon there is another negative piece of news, stock markets react accordingly," said Anne-Kristin Yasuda, strategist at Landesbank Berlin. Credit Suisse shares slid 5.5 percent and were the strongest negative weight on the European benchmark index after the Swiss bank cautioned it was unlikely to be profitable in the first quarter due to big debt writedowns. Allianz fell 1.6 percent after the German insurer gave a bearish outlook for this year and next, saying its goal to increase operating profit by an average 10 percent had become more difficult. Falling oil and commodity prices drove mining and energy stocks lower. Anglo American fell 4.4 percent, BHP Billiton fell 4.1 percent and Rio Tinto eased 4.6 percent, while BP and Total each fell around 1 perce
